    <!-- Content sections -->
    <mj-section background-color="#ffffff">
      <mj-column>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Sticky situation</h2>  
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Happy accidents, as we call them, often start from not-so-happy beginnings. The story of the ubiquitous Post-it Note is no exception. What is now a staple of office supplies <strong>began as an embarrassing mishap</strong>, one that, like many great inventions, only found success because of the persistence of the right people.
          </p>
        </mj-text>

        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/Spencer-Silver-Art-Fry-3M-Post-it-Note-pad.png" alt="Spencer Silver, a 3M adhesive scientist, and Art Fry, a 3M product development researcher, pictured holding a Post-it Note pad" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>Spencer Silver, a 3M adhesive scientist, and Art Fry, a 3M product development researcher, pictured holding a Post-it Note pad. Credits: media.moneyforward</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>

        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          It all started in 1968. Spencer Silver, a <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-22-03-2025-research-scientist-at-3m" target="_blank">research scientist at 3M</a>, was tasked with developing a super-strong adhesive suitable for aerospace applications that could withstand extreme conditions. However, things didn‚Äôt go according to plan. <strong>Silver accidentally added too much of a particular monomer</strong>, resulting in a sticky adhesive that didn‚Äôt actually stick.  
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">He birthed acrylate co-polymer microspheres, a weak, <strong>pressure-sensitive ‚Äúlow-tack‚Äù adhesive</strong>. The odd thing about these microspheres was that they created a bond that could be peeled away quickly without leaving residue, and they could be reused multiple times. Silver had technically failed at his assigned task, but he was convinced that his accidental invention had potential. The problem? No one could figure out what to do with it. 
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column> 
    </mj-section>

