    <mj-column>
      <mj-spacer height="14px" />
          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Failure to launch</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Years later, <strong>Art Fry, a product development researcher at 3M</strong> and a choir singer, had a very specific problem; his bookmarks kept falling out of his hymnal during practice. He needed a way to mark pages without damaging them. Remembering Silver‚Äôs seminar, he found the perfect use for the infamous ‚Äúlow-tack‚Äù glue. What if this ‚Äúnon-sticky‚Äù glue could be used on paper to create a removable bookmark?
         </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Fry and Silver <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-22-03-2025-initially-focussed-on-bookmarks" target="_blank">initially focused on bookmarks</a>. However, they soon realized these sticky notes were perfect for jotting down quick messages and reminders. Within 3M, their team began using prototype notes for internal communication, and the product's utility became undeniable. <strong>Together, they created a new form of communication</strong>. Despite its usefulness, management at 3M remained skeptical.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">In 1973, a leadership change gave Silver a chance to pitch the product, but the only viable concept they could propose was a reusable bulletin board. When Fry suggested applying the adhesive directly to paper, the product faced another hurdle. The scientists needed to <strong>perfect the glue so that it would adhere properly but still be peeled away cleanly</strong>. This challenge was solved, but senior management doubted the product‚Äôs viability and shelved it again.</p>
          </mj-text>
          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">The duo that made it stick</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">It wasn‚Äôt until 1977 that 3M finally tested the product in four cities. The results were disappointing. <strong>Sales were dismal, seemingly proving management right in their skepticism</strong>. But Fry and Nicholson, the new products laboratory manager, refused to give up. They believed the problem wasn‚Äôt the product itself but the lack of consumer awareness.</p>
          </mj-text>

          <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/Arthur-Fry-lab-research.png" alt="Arthur Fry in the lab" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
           <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>Arthur Fry in the lab. Credits: The Chemical Engineer</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>

          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">So, in 1978, 3M launched a massive sampling campaign called the <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-22-03-2025-boise-blitz" target="_blank">‚ÄúBoise Blitz,‚Äù</a> named after Boise, Idaho, where the effort began. <strong>Companies were given free samples, and 3M tracked how many reordered the product</strong>. 90% of companies that received samples placed reorders. This finally convinced 3M of the product‚Äôs potential, leading to its official launch in US stores on April 6, 1980, under the name ‚ÄúPost-it Notes.‚Äù</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Today, Post-it Notes are 3M, the Minnesota-based company‚Äôs most successful product and a global phenomenon. The iconic canary yellow color was chosen simply because it was the color of scrap paper available in the lab. <strong>In 2010, Spencer Silver and Art Fry were inducted into the National Inventors Hall of Fame</strong>, a fitting recognition for two men who turned an accidental failure into one of the most successful office products.</p>
          </mj-text> 
      </mj-column>
